# Backend Core Rules

## Scope

- Apply to backend services, APIs, workers, and jobs.
- Keep domain-specific or project-specific constraints in project overrides.

## Architecture And Boundaries

- Separate transport, application logic, and persistence responsibilities.
- Keep business logic out of controllers/handlers; use service/use-case layers.
- Depend on interfaces/ports where possible to reduce coupling.

## API And Contract Discipline

- Keep request/response contracts explicit and backward compatible by default.
- Validate and sanitize all external input at API/message boundaries.
- For breaking API/schema changes, document impact and migration notes.

## Data And Persistence

- Use transactional boundaries intentionally for multi-step writes.
- Avoid N+1 queries and unbounded scans on critical paths.
- Prefer idempotent behavior for retryable operations and jobs.

## Errors And Observability

- Use structured errors with actionable context.
- Log enough metadata for tracing, but never log secrets or sensitive data.
- Emit metrics/traces for critical flows and failure paths.

## Security Baseline

- Enforce authn/authz checks at trusted boundaries.
- Never hardcode secrets, keys, or credentials.
- Apply least-privilege access for data stores and external integrations.

## Testing Baseline

- Add or update unit/integration tests for meaningful logic changes.
- Verify contract changes with tests or schema checks.
